Gem is sessionnotfoundexception not a valid webdriver exception?

Gemini said
It’s definitely a valid and—honestly—quite frustrating exception to run into. While it might feel like your code is gaslighting you, SessionNotfoundException is a very real part of the Selenium WebDriver library.

In short: It means the WebDriver is trying to talk to a browser session that no longer exists.

Why is this happening?
Think of the "Session ID" as a temporary phone number the WebDriver uses to call the browser. This exception pops up when the WebDriver tries to dial that number and gets a "disconnected" tone. Here are the usual suspects:

The driver.quit() was called too early: You might have a line of code that closes the session, but then a later line tries to interact with the browser again.

The Browser Crashed: If the browser window closes unexpectedly (manual intervention or a system crash), the session ID becomes a ghost.

Server Timeout: If you are using a remote grid (like Selenium Grid, SauceLabs, or BrowserStack), the server might have timed out and killed the session due to inactivity.

Incompatibility: Occasionally, a major version mismatch between your Browser (e.g., Chrome 134) and your Driver (ChromeDriver) can cause the session to drop abruptly.

How to fix it
Since it's a legitimate class, you can actually catch it in your code to handle it gracefully.

Language	Typical Import Path
Java	org.openqa.selenium.NoSuchSessionException
Python	selenium.common.exceptions.NoSuchSessionException
C#	OpenQA.Selenium.NoSuchSessionException
Note: Depending on your specific language binding and Selenium version, it is often officially categorized as NoSuchSessionException. If you are seeing SessionNotFoundException specifically, you might be looking at an older version of Selenium (v2/v3) or a specific driver implementation.

Quick Checklist
Check your loops: Ensure driver.quit() isn't inside a loop where it kills the session before the next iteration.

Update your drivers: Ensure your WebDriver matches your browser version.

Check for "Zombies": Make sure old WebDriver processes aren't hanging around in your Task Manager/Activity Monitor.

