Elementnotvisibleexception

Gemini said
What it means
"I found it, but I can't touch it."

If NoSuchElementException is not finding the cereal at all, ElementNotVisibleException is seeing the cereal box on the shelf but realizing it’s hidden behind a giant "Staff Only" sign or tucked inside a closed cabinet. The element exists in the code (the HTML), but it’s hidden from the user's view.

Why it usually happens
Hidden by Design: The element is technically on the page, but its CSS is set to display: none or visibility: hidden.

Overlapped: Another element (like a "Loading" spinner or a pop-up overlay) is sitting on top of it.

Too Small to Click: The element has a height or width of 0 pixels.

Not Scrolled In: Sometimes (depending on the driver), Selenium won't interact with it if it hasn't been scrolled into the viewport yet.

How to fix it
Wait for Visibility: Instead of just waiting for the element to exist, use an Explicit Wait for visibilityOfElementLocated.

Check for Overlays: Make sure a "Cookie Consent" banner or a "Sign up for our Newsletter" pop-up isn't blocking the view.

JavaScript Click: If you’re desperate and the element is definitely there, you can use a "JS Click" which bypasses the visibility check entirely—though this is considered a "cheat" in automation!

