No such frame exception

Gemini said
What it means
"I’m trying to enter a room that doesn't exist."

Imagine you are in a large office building (the webpage). You are told to go into "Office 404" to sign a document. You walk to where it should be, but there is no door with that name. You're standing in the hallway confused because you were told the room was there, but you can't find the entrance.

Why it usually happens
The Wrong Name/Index: You told Selenium to switch to a frame named "login-frame," but the actual ID is "LoginFrame" (case sensitivity matters!) or the index number is wrong.

Timing Issues: The page is loading, and you tried to switch to the frame before the browser had a chance to build it.

The "Nested" Trap: You are already inside "Frame A" and tried to switch to "Frame B," but "Frame B" is back out in the main hallway. Selenium can't see "Frame B" from inside "Frame A."

The Frame is Gone: A dynamic advertisement or a pop-up frame closed or refreshed right as you tried to jump in.

How to fix it
Check your spelling: Ensure the id or name of the iframe matches exactly what is in the HTML.

Go back to "Home" first: If you are moving between frames, use driver.switchTo().defaultContent(); to go back to the main page before trying to enter a new frame.

Wait for it: Use an Explicit Wait specifically for the frame: ExpectedConditions.frameToBeAvailableAndSwitchToIt. This waits for the frame to exist and moves you inside it in one move.

