No alert present exception

Gemini said
What it means
"I reached for a pop-up, but I grabbed thin air."

Imagine you’re expecting a "Surprise!" party. You jump through the front door with your hands up, ready to catch confetti—but the room is empty and the lights are off. You tried to interact with a browser alert (those little "OK/Cancel" boxes at the top of the screen), but the alert wasn't there when you reached for it.

Why it usually happens
The Speed Racer: Your script is faster than the browser. It tries to click "OK" before the alert has actually finished popping up.

The "Auto-Closer": Sometimes, clicking a button triggers an alert that then disappears instantly due to a script error or another overlapping action.

Wrong Trigger: You clicked a button that you thought would trigger an alert, but it actually opened a "Modal" (a fancy HTML pop-up). Selenium treats "Alerts" and "Modals" very differently.

How to fix it
Wait for it: This is the #1 fix. Use an Explicit Wait for alertIsPresent(). This tells Selenium to keep checking for a few seconds before giving up.

Check the Type: If it’s a styled box with images or custom buttons, it’s likely a Modal, not a browser Alert. You don't "switch" to those; you just find them like regular elements.

Try/Catch: Since alerts can be unpredictable, wrapping your alert code in a try-catch block is a common way to handle cases where an alert might only show up sometimes.

