You said
No such window exception

Gemini said
What it means
"I’m looking for a tab that just closed or never existed."

Imagine you are browsing the web and you click a link that opens a new tab. You turn your head for a second, and when you look back, you try to type into that new tab—but it’s gone. You’re left staring at an empty space. Selenium is trying to send a command to a specific window ID (handle) that the browser no longer recognizes.

Why it usually happens
The "Self-Closing" Tab: You clicked a "Download" or "Logout" button that opens a temporary window, which then closes itself automatically once the task is done.

Manual Interference: You (the human) physically closed the browser tab while the script was still running.

The driver.close() Trap: You used driver.close() (which kills the current tab) but then forgot to tell Selenium to "switch" its focus back to the main window. It’s now stranded in a ghost session.

Pop-up Blockers: Your script expected a new window to pop up, but the browser blocked it. Selenium has a "handle" for a window that technically never opened.

How to fix it
Switch Back: Whenever you close a window or tab, always immediately use driver.switchTo().window(originalHandle); to put Selenium back on solid ground.

Count your Windows: Before switching, check driver.getWindowHandles().size() to make sure the number of open windows is what you expect.

Wait for the New Window: Use an Explicit Wait for numberOfWindowsToBe(2) before trying to switch to a second tab. This ensures the browser has actually finished opening it.

