Session not found exception

Gemini said
What it means
"I’m trying to talk to a ghost."

This is the one we started with! If the other exceptions are like looking for a missing item in a house, SessionNotFoundException is like the house itself has burned down. You are sending commands to a browser that is no longer connected to your script.

Why it usually happens
The "Accidental Exit": You called driver.quit() or driver.close() in your code, but then tried to do one more thing (like taking a screenshot) after the browser was already dead.

The Manual Close: You (the human) closed the browser window while the script was still running.

The Browser Crash: Chrome or Firefox crashed in the background because it ran out of memory or hit a major bug.

The "Timeout" (Grid/Cloud): If you're using a service like SauceLabs or Selenium Grid, they will kill your session if your script sits idle for too long (usually 60–300 seconds) to save resources.

How to fix it
Check your quit() timing: Make sure driver.quit() is the absolute last line of your test suite.

Don't close the last window: If you use driver.close() on the only open tab, the entire session often ends. Use driver.quit() for a clean exit instead.

Update your Driver: If the browser crashes constantly, your chromedriver or geckodriver might be outdated and incompatible with your browser version.

Check for "Zombies": Sometimes a previous crashed test leaves a "ghost" process behind. Restart your IDE or clear your task manager of any stray driver processes.

